    body: 'Four of the SOC 2 gap items called out in docs/compliance/soc2-mapping.md close in a single PR. SECURITY.md at the repo root names security@velox.dev as the responsible-disclosure inbox with a 5-business-day triage SLA, 30-day patch-landing target for high/critical issues, explicit in-scope and out-of-scope lists (the binary, schema, dashboard, encryption-at-rest + audit-log + RLS guarantees in scope; operator deploy environment, third-party services, DoS via traffic flooding out of scope), and a safe-harbor clause for good-faith research — closes the largest CC2.3 gap. CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md references Contributor Covenant 2.1 verbatim with conduct@velox.dev as the reporting inbox and a separate conduct-escalation@velox.dev for concerns about the maintainer — closes CC1.1. CODEOWNERS at the repo root assigns the maintainer as default reviewer for every path with comments outlining how the file should split per-domain ownership as contributors join — closes CC5.2. .github/workflows/ci.yml drops continue-on-error: true from the govulncheck step so a stdlib or module vulnerability with a known fix now blocks PR merges (CI uses Go 1.25.9 and reports clean at time of merge) — closes CC6.8. The SOC 2 mapping doc is updated to flip the four closed items in the "top gaps" list and rewrite the inline narratives in CC1.1 / CC2.3 / CC5.2 / CC6.8 so the doc stays the source of truth on what is done versus what is outstanding.',
    bullets: [
      'SECURITY.md: 5-business-day triage commitment, 30-day patch-landing target for high/critical (90 days for medium, best-effort for low), explicit in-scope list (Velox binary, internal/ + pkg/, migration runner + schema, web-v2 dashboard, deploy artifacts, all documented security guarantees from the encryption-at-rest + soc2-mapping + audit-log-retention docs), explicit out-of-scope list (operator deploy environment, vulnerabilities in third-party services, configuration mistakes, DoS via traffic flooding, self-XSS / social engineering / physical attacks, reports against forks before reproducing on canonical main). Includes a hardening status section that openly lists the still-outstanding gaps (key rotation tooling, MFA on dashboard, SAST in CI, image signing, threat model doc, external pentest) so contributors can see where help is welcome. Safe-harbor clause documents the four conditions for protected good-faith research.',
      'CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md adopts Contributor Covenant 2.1 by reference rather than vendoring the canonical text — same audit value (project has a CoC, cites the standard, names enforcement contacts) without re-vendoring text that could drift from the upstream version. Names two distinct inboxes: conduct@velox.dev for concerns about contributors and conduct-escalation@velox.dev for concerns about the maintainer (since the maintainer cannot adjudicate a complaint against themselves). Documents an 18-month private incident-log retention to match the audit-log-retention default at docs/ops/audit-log-retention.md.',
      'CODEOWNERS at the repo root: today the project is single-maintainer so the file is a one-line `* @sagarsuperuser` catch-all that ensures GitHub auto-assigns the maintainer as required reviewer on every PR (the SOC 2 CC8.1 evidence artifact: every change reviewed). Inline comments outline the per-domain ownership shape that should replace the catch-all as contributors join — separate owners for internal/billing, internal/payment, web-v2, charts/ + deploy/, .github/, docs/compliance/ — so the next maintainer onboarding is a copy-paste rather than a design exercise.',
      'govulncheck is now a hard CI gate: removing the `continue-on-error: true` line from .github/workflows/ci.yml means a known-CVE in the Go stdlib or any imported module with a fix available will fail the build. Setup-go pulls the latest patch in the 1.25 series (currently 1.25.9 in CI) — local Go installs lagging behind will see different output (e.g. a 1.25.1 install reports 20 stdlib vulns); CI is the source of truth. Verified by inspecting the latest pre-merge CI run on main showing "No vulnerabilities found." The change does not introduce a flaky failure mode: govulncheck only reports CVEs whose fixes are available in newer patch versions, so as long as setup-go pulls a current patch, the gate stays green.',
      'docs/compliance/soc2-mapping.md updated in three places: CC1.1 narrative rewritten to cite the new CODE_OF_CONDUCT + CODEOWNERS rather than describe their absence; CC2.3 narrative rewritten to cite the new SECURITY.md including the 5-business-day SLA, 30-day patch target, and safe-harbor clause; CC5.2 + CC6.8 narratives rewritten to cite govulncheck as a hard CI gate rather than `continue-on-error: true`. The "Top gaps to close before a Type 1" list flips items 2, 4, 6, 7 to ~~strikethrough~~ + bold "Closed" with the closure mechanism inline. The remaining gaps (key rotation, MFA, SAST, status page, image signing, threat model, customer-notification template, quarterly tabletop, vendor risk-review log, pentest, dormant-key sweeper, anomaly detection, fine-grained API key scopes) keep their original ranking — items 1 + 3 + 5 + 8-17.',
    ],
